NOTES_NUMBERS_29_32 = {
    29: {
        1: 'FEAST OF TRUMPETS (Yom Teruah): The first day of the seventh month -- later known as Rosh Hashanah. The blowing of trumpets signals the beginning of the most sacred month in the Israelite calendar. ESCHATOLOGY: The last trumpet will announce the return of Christ (1 Thess 4:16; 1 Cor 15:52; Rev 11:15). The Feast of Trumpets awaits its ultimate fulfillment.',
        7: 'DAY OF ATONEMENT (Yom Kippur): The most solemn day in Israel\'s calendar -- the only commanded fast. \'Humble your souls\' (te\'annu et nafshoteikhem). On this day the high priest enters the Holy of Holies with blood to atone for the nation\'s sins (Lev 16). CHRIST: Hebrews 9:11-12 declares that Christ entered the heavenly Holy of Holies with His own blood, obtaining eternal redemption. Yom Kippur is fulfilled at the cross.',
        12: 'FEAST OF TABERNACLES (Sukkot): A seven-day celebration of joy and harvest thanksgiving, during which Israel dwells in booths (sukkot) to remember the wilderness wandering. The bull offerings descend from 13 to 7 over seven days (total = 70 bulls). The rabbis noted that 70 bulls correspond to the 70 nations of Genesis 10 -- Israel offers sacrifice on behalf of all the world. CHRIST: John 7:37-39 records Jesus\' proclamation at the Feast of Tabernacles: \'If anyone is thirsty, let him come to Me and drink.\' The feast of ingathering points to the final harvest of all nations into God\'s kingdom.',
        35: 'THE EIGHTH DAY (Shemini Atzeret): A separate, solemn assembly on the eighth day -- one bull, one ram, seven lambs. After seven days of cosmic, universal offering (70 bulls for 70 nations), the eighth day is intimate: one bull for Israel alone. The eighth day transcends the seven-day week of creation -- it represents the new creation, the age to come. CHRIST: The eighth day is the day of resurrection (Sunday, the first/eighth day). New creation has begun in Christ.',
    },
    30: {
        2: 'THE SANCTITY OF VOWS: A man\'s vow is absolutely binding -- \'he shall not violate his word.\' In a culture where verbal commitments were the basis of all agreements, breaking a vow was breaking faith with God Himself, since vows were made \'to the LORD.\' Jesus reaffirms: \'Let your yes be yes, and your no be no\' (Matt 5:37).',
        15: 'PROTECTIVE AUTHORITY: The husband who annuls late \'shall bear her guilt\' -- he takes the responsibility onto himself. This is substitutionary headship: the authority figure bears the consequences of his own decisions. CHRIST: The ultimate head who bears the guilt of His bride, the church (Eph 5:25-27).',
    },
    31: {
        8: 'BALAAM\'S DEATH: Balaam, the prophet who blessed Israel but then counseled Balak to seduce them (Rev 2:14), dies by the sword in battle. He spoke true prophecy but lived a false life. He saw the star of Jacob but chose the wages of unrighteousness. His death is a permanent warning: spiritual gifts without spiritual obedience lead to destruction.',
        16: 'BALAAM\'S COUNSEL REVEALED: The Midianite women\'s seduction of Israel (ch. 25) was Balaam\'s idea. Unable to curse Israel spiritually, he advised corrupting them morally. What the angel with the sword could not stop, what four oracles could not reverse, was nearly accomplished through sexual temptation and religious syncretism. The most dangerous attack on God\'s people comes not from without but from within.',
        49: 'NOT ONE MISSING: After a full-scale war, not a single Israelite soldier was killed. This is not natural; it is miraculous. The officers\' gold offering is a response of gratitude for divine protection that defied all military probability.',
    },
    32: {
        6: 'MOSES\' ALARM: Moses immediately sees the parallel with Kadesh-barnea. Tribal self-interest that weakens the whole community is the same sin that destroyed the previous generation. Moses confronts it directly.',
        14: 'A BROOD OF SINFUL MEN: Moses\' rebuke is harsh because the stakes are existential. If the Transjordan tribes refuse to fight, the entire conquest fails, and the new generation repeats the old generation\'s sin. The word \'brood\' (tarbut) means \'increase/offspring\' -- they are reproducing their fathers\' rebellion.',
        23: 'YOUR SIN WILL FIND YOU OUT: One of the most quoted proverbs from Numbers. Sin has consequences that cannot be evaded. Even if hidden from men, sin is never hidden from God. The verb \'find\' (matsa) implies active pursuit -- sin hunts down the sinner.',
        33: 'THE HALF-TRIBE OF MANASSEH: Manasseh appears for the first time in the negotiation, though they were not part of the original request. They apparently joined during the discussion or were added by Moses. This split of Manasseh -- half in Transjordan, half in Canaan -- will have lasting implications for tribal unity.',
    },
}
